00:00:13.638 --> 00:00:15.598 position:50% align:center
[ADACHI] At the last match,
you guys definitely

00:00:15.682 --> 00:00:17.350 position:50% align:center
discovered a new weapon.

00:00:17.434 --> 00:00:19.144 position:50% align:center
But you can't let that
fool you into thinking

00:00:19.227 --> 00:00:21.271 position:50% align:center
you've already
reached the end goal.

00:00:21.354 --> 00:00:22.856 position:50% align:center
You should see it
as a starting point

00:00:22.939 --> 00:00:25.483 position:50% align:center
for developing even better
moves to compete with.

00:00:25.567 --> 00:00:27.152 position:50% align:center
Just keep in mind,
if you sacrifice

00:00:27.235 --> 00:00:29.863 position:50% align:center
team cohesion for flair,
then you're done.

00:00:29.946 --> 00:00:32.032 position:50% align:center
Wing and guards,
widen your fields of view.

00:00:32.115 --> 00:00:33.742 position:50% align:center
Be mindful of the
triangle formation

00:00:33.825 --> 00:00:35.410 position:50% align:center
and adjust accordingly.

00:00:35.493 --> 00:00:37.620 position:50% align:center
The key is to aim equally
for synchronization

00:00:37.704 --> 00:00:38.830 position:50% align:center
and skill.

00:00:38.913 --> 00:00:40.665 position:50% align:center
You should be striving
for a perfect union

00:00:40.749 --> 00:00:42.459 position:50% align:center
of unexpected, dynamic movement

00:00:42.542 --> 00:00:45.045 position:50% align:center
and a precisely
calculated routine.

00:00:45.128 --> 00:00:47.255 position:50% align:center
Frankly, as far as
skilled individuals go,

00:00:47.339 --> 00:00:49.966 position:50% align:center
St. Clavis Gakuin and
Chutei University High

00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:51.051 position:50% align:center
both have us beat.

00:00:51.134 --> 00:00:52.719 position:50% align:center
But the skill of
each team as a whole

00:00:52.802 --> 00:00:54.471 position:50% align:center
is a different story.

00:00:54.554 --> 00:00:56.056 position:50% align:center
All right, let's get to work.

00:00:56.723 --> 00:00:57.724 position:50% align:center
[GROUP]
Yes, sir!

00:02:33.445 --> 00:02:35.196 position:50% align:center
[KUBOTA]
Aiming to perfect both our style

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:37.073 position:50% align:center
and the issues the
coach pointed out,

00:02:37.157 --> 00:02:39.117 position:50% align:center
we began to practice.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.411 position:50% align:center
Naturally, it wasn't
all smooth sailing,

00:02:41.494 --> 00:02:43.413 position:50% align:center
and we didn't always
see eye to eye.

00:02:43.496 --> 00:02:46.458 position:50% align:center
But we were united in our
goal of refining the routine,

00:02:46.541 --> 00:02:47.917 position:50% align:center
and I think everyone
could agree that we

00:02:48.001 --> 00:02:50.462 position:50% align:center
improved greatly by the day.

00:02:50.545 --> 00:02:52.881 position:50% align:center
Then, we finally skated in
the seventh competition

00:02:52.964 --> 00:02:53.965 position:50% align:center
of the series.

00:02:54.049 --> 00:02:56.259 position:50% align:center
Our third and last
preliminary match.

00:02:56.343 --> 00:02:57.719 position:50% align:center
Everything hinged on it.

00:02:59.554 --> 00:03:02.307 position:50% align:center
We won the short
program and free skate.

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:05.060 position:50% align:center
So naturally, we came
in first and won the day.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:10.023 position:50% align:center
We're fourth overall!

00:03:10.106 --> 00:03:11.816 position:50% align:center
Yeah, we've pretty
much secured a spot

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:13.193 position:50% align:center
at the Grand Prix finals.

00:03:13.276 --> 00:03:14.319 position:50% align:center
[GROUP]
Yes!

00:03:15.737 --> 00:03:18.073 position:50% align:center
[SASUGAI] The fourth competition
against Shinozaki's team

00:03:18.156 --> 00:03:19.282 position:50% align:center
did it for us.

00:03:19.366 --> 00:03:22.035 position:50% align:center
That score would've
topped any other match.

00:03:22.118 --> 00:03:24.371 position:50% align:center
It made up for our loss
at the first competition.

00:03:26.164 --> 00:03:27.415 position:50% align:center
Will you stop sulking?

00:03:27.499 --> 00:03:29.000 position:50% align:center
I'm not sulking!

00:03:29.084 --> 00:03:30.710 position:50% align:center
So, Taiga's team's first?

00:03:30.794 --> 00:03:32.170 position:50% align:center
I guess we expected that.

00:03:32.253 --> 00:03:34.339 position:50% align:center
Well, they do have Shinozaki.

00:03:34.422 --> 00:03:36.257 position:50% align:center
And Chutei High with
the Ishikawa brothers

00:03:36.341 --> 00:03:38.593 position:50% align:center
is second, huh?
No surprise there.

00:03:38.677 --> 00:03:39.886 position:50% align:center
Who's in third and fifth?

00:03:39.969 --> 00:03:41.805 position:50% align:center
[SASUGAI] Hokkaido's Eimei
Academy and Ehime's

00:03:41.888 --> 00:03:43.848 position:50% align:center
Matsuyama Fukuonji.

00:03:43.932 --> 00:03:45.850 position:50% align:center
Both are first timers
to the finals,

00:03:45.934 --> 00:03:48.228 position:50% align:center
and it's the first school
from Ehime ever.

00:03:48.311 --> 00:03:50.980 position:50% align:center
The top five teams are pretty
much set for the finals.

00:03:51.064 --> 00:03:52.524 position:50% align:center
[AKIMITSU]
Really?

00:03:52.607 --> 00:03:54.442 position:50% align:center
[SASUGAI] There's a wide point
gap between fifth and sixth.

00:03:54.526 --> 00:03:56.653 position:50% align:center
I just don't see it
happening, you know?

00:03:56.736 --> 00:03:57.821 position:50% align:center
Not now.

00:03:57.904 --> 00:03:59.364 position:50% align:center
There aren't any schools
that can clear it

00:03:59.447 --> 00:04:01.032 position:50% align:center
with a single match remaining.

00:04:01.116 --> 00:04:02.992 position:50% align:center
So, who's in the
running for sixth?

00:04:03.076 --> 00:04:06.246 position:50% align:center
There are two left
who stand a chance:

00:04:06.329 --> 00:04:09.040 position:50% align:center
Himekawa's team and Kuonji's.

00:04:10.583 --> 00:04:13.003 position:50% align:center
Wow, you're amazing, Kuonji!

00:04:13.086 --> 00:04:15.046 position:50% align:center
Didn't you just establish
the club this year?

00:04:15.130 --> 00:04:16.464 position:50% align:center
Oh, you're too kind.

00:04:16.548 --> 00:04:18.800 position:50% align:center
It's all thanks to
these guys' hard work.

00:04:18.883 --> 00:04:20.010 position:50% align:center
[MC A]
Well, you've come this far,

00:04:20.093 --> 00:04:21.761 position:50% align:center
so I assume you
aim to take first

00:04:21.845 --> 00:04:23.430 position:50% align:center
in the eighth competition
to qualify for

00:04:23.513 --> 00:04:25.056 position:50% align:center
the Grand Prix finals!

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:27.017 position:50% align:center
We can't let you down
now, can we?

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:28.810 position:50% align:center
We'll do our best!

00:04:28.893 --> 00:04:31.646 position:50% align:center
We'll be rooting for you.
Let's hear it, everyone!

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:33.064 position:50% align:center
--[GROUP] Miá*Leon!
--Noa!

00:04:33.148 --> 00:04:34.524 position:50% align:center
--[GROUP] Miá*Leon!
--Noa!

00:04:34.607 --> 00:04:36.860 position:50% align:center
--[GROUP] Miá*Leon!
--Noa!

00:04:36.943 --> 00:04:38.778 position:50% align:center
I hope you'll
cheer them on, too!

00:04:38.862 --> 00:04:41.281 position:50% align:center
Yes, please, we love you!

00:04:41.364 --> 00:04:42.615 position:50% align:center
[GROUP]
What?!

00:04:46.077 --> 00:04:47.620 position:50% align:center
Hey. What's up, guys?

00:04:47.704 --> 00:04:48.913 position:50% align:center
Number Two Prince.

00:04:48.997 --> 00:04:50.290 position:50% align:center
[KIRIYAMA]
What are you doing here?

00:04:50.373 --> 00:04:52.292 position:50% align:center
You were like, just on TV.

00:04:52.375 --> 00:04:53.626 position:50% align:center
Yeah. I just left there.

00:04:55.295 --> 00:04:56.796 position:50% align:center
Can I have a minute?

00:05:01.301 --> 00:05:04.220 position:50% align:center
[MAESHIMA] What'd you bring
me all the way out here for?

00:05:04.304 --> 00:05:05.305 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI]
Sorry!

00:05:06.348 --> 00:05:08.516 position:50% align:center
I came to apologize.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:10.310 position:50% align:center
I invited you to
be a part of my team

00:05:10.393 --> 00:05:12.562 position:50% align:center
a little while back,
do you remember that?

00:05:12.645 --> 00:05:15.899 position:50% align:center
Yeah, I seem to remember
turning you down.

00:05:15.982 --> 00:05:18.318 position:50% align:center
Well, now I'd like
to retract that offer.

00:05:18.401 --> 00:05:19.736 position:50% align:center
But I already refused it!

00:05:19.819 --> 00:05:22.364 position:50% align:center
The thing is, all my teammates
were complete amateurs

00:05:22.447 --> 00:05:23.531 position:50% align:center
in the beginning.

00:05:24.908 --> 00:05:26.451 position:50% align:center
But they worked
hard for the team,

00:05:26.534 --> 00:05:28.411 position:50% align:center
finding spare moments to
in their busy schedules

00:05:28.495 --> 00:05:31.706 position:50% align:center
to practice, on top of the idol
stuff that they handle.

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:33.625 position:50% align:center
It's at least partly
thanks to their efforts

00:05:33.708 --> 00:05:36.127 position:50% align:center
that the Grand Prix finals
are now within reach.

00:05:36.211 --> 00:05:37.420 position:50% align:center
I'm not gonna lie, though,

00:05:37.504 --> 00:05:39.589 position:50% align:center
it's almost totally
thanks to me!

00:05:39.673 --> 00:05:40.799 position:50% align:center
Jeez.

00:05:40.882 --> 00:05:44.719 position:50% align:center
But I'm not kidding
about all their work.

00:05:44.803 --> 00:05:46.888 position:50% align:center
This team committed
to following me despite

00:05:46.971 --> 00:05:48.765 position:50% align:center
their various circumstances,

00:05:48.848 --> 00:05:51.101 position:50% align:center
and now I feel like
I can't betray them.

00:05:51.184 --> 00:05:53.770 position:50% align:center
So, I'm sorry, but the
offer is off the table.

00:05:53.853 --> 00:05:55.021 position:50% align:center
Hold on, I never even--

00:05:55.105 --> 00:05:57.023 position:50% align:center
And in exchange,
I'm going to build a team

00:05:57.107 --> 00:05:59.526 position:50% align:center
and invite all of you
guys to join up, 'kay?

00:05:59.609 --> 00:06:00.985 position:50% align:center
And that's a promise.

00:06:01.069 --> 00:06:02.028 position:50% align:center
But you really don't--

00:06:02.112 --> 00:06:03.446 position:50% align:center
I'm so glad.

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:04.906 position:50% align:center
Though I had no doubt you
would consent, of course.

00:06:04.989 --> 00:06:06.324 position:50% align:center
Would you listen to me?

00:06:06.408 --> 00:06:09.160 position:50% align:center
Oh, sorry, but I'm
afraid I've got to run.

00:06:09.244 --> 00:06:10.120 position:50% align:center
See ya later.

00:06:10.203 --> 00:06:11.496 position:50% align:center
Wait just a minute!

00:06:11.579 --> 00:06:14.290 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI] Oh, right,
I almost forgot, didn't I?

00:06:14.374 --> 00:06:17.168 position:50% align:center
My team will be the champions
of the Grand Prix finals.

00:06:17.252 --> 00:06:18.253 position:50% align:center
[phone rings]

00:06:18.336 --> 00:06:20.005 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI]
Yes, hello, is my manager there?

00:06:20.088 --> 00:06:22.799 position:50% align:center
It's about my interview tonight.
Gimme those deets!

00:06:22.882 --> 00:06:24.551 position:50% align:center
[laughing]

00:06:27.053 --> 00:06:29.014 position:50% align:center
[SHINOZAKI]
What do I think of Noa Kuonji?

00:06:29.097 --> 00:06:30.056 position:50% align:center
[HIMURO]
Yeah.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:31.307 position:50% align:center
You've competed
against him before,

00:06:31.391 --> 00:06:33.393 position:50% align:center
so I thought you might
have a few thoughts.

00:06:33.476 --> 00:06:35.186 position:50% align:center
Do you?

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:37.147 position:50% align:center
Look, he was at the
competitions in Montreal

00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:39.149 position:50% align:center
and Vancouver when
we were all juniors.

00:06:39.232 --> 00:06:41.609 position:50% align:center
Aw. I do love maple syrup.

00:06:41.693 --> 00:06:43.028 position:50% align:center
[MICHINAGA]
You forgot about him?

00:06:43.111 --> 00:06:44.154 position:50% align:center
A loud nuisance.

00:06:44.237 --> 00:06:46.489 position:50% align:center
What's he like as a competitor?

00:06:46.573 --> 00:06:48.116 position:50% align:center
Well, Kurayoshi?

00:06:48.199 --> 00:06:49.993 position:50% align:center
He has a unique personality.

00:06:50.076 --> 00:06:52.579 position:50% align:center
He's always positive and
he isn't afraid to mess up.

00:06:52.662 --> 00:06:55.540 position:50% align:center
I got the impression he
liked using risky elements.

00:06:55.623 --> 00:06:56.958 position:50% align:center
Although, back in those days,

00:06:57.042 --> 00:06:58.793 position:50% align:center
he didn't quite have
the build for it yet.

00:06:58.877 --> 00:07:00.211 position:50% align:center
He made a lot of mistakes.

00:07:00.295 --> 00:07:01.838 position:50% align:center
Does he have the
build for it now?

00:07:01.921 --> 00:07:03.131 position:50% align:center
I don't know.

00:07:03.214 --> 00:07:05.383 position:50% align:center
It's all about body weight
and muscle mass.

00:07:05.467 --> 00:07:07.510 position:50% align:center
From the look of it,
he could be right on track.

00:07:07.594 --> 00:07:09.804 position:50% align:center
I know the talk's
all about Kuonji,

00:07:09.888 --> 00:07:12.474 position:50% align:center
but we should actually watch
out for Himekawa, too.

00:07:12.557 --> 00:07:13.600 position:50% align:center
Definitely.

00:07:13.683 --> 00:07:15.602 position:50% align:center
Terauchi's team lost
a valuable player

00:07:15.685 --> 00:07:17.979 position:50% align:center
when Himekawa left and
took his skill set with him.

00:07:18.063 --> 00:07:19.397 position:50% align:center
I've known him since I was a kid

00:07:19.481 --> 00:07:22.150 position:50% align:center
and I can tell you he's the
exact opposite of Kuonji

00:07:22.233 --> 00:07:24.402 position:50% align:center
and he's always
super consistent.

00:07:24.486 --> 00:07:26.988 position:50% align:center
And at a really high level, too.

00:07:27.072 --> 00:07:29.991 position:50% align:center
To say he's not the talkative
type is an understatement.

00:07:30.075 --> 00:07:31.701 position:50% align:center
But deep down,
he's got this fiery,

00:07:31.785 --> 00:07:33.870 position:50% align:center
competitive spirit
that really drives him.

00:07:38.541 --> 00:07:39.542 position:50% align:center
[IGARASHI grunts]

00:07:40.835 --> 00:07:41.795 position:50% align:center
Are you okay?

00:07:41.878 --> 00:07:43.380 position:50% align:center
Yeah. I'm fine.

00:07:43.463 --> 00:07:46.299 position:50% align:center
Hey, sorry,
I'll keep up next time.

00:07:46.383 --> 00:07:47.759 position:50% align:center
I know you will.

00:07:47.842 --> 00:07:50.011 position:50% align:center
[KUMADA]
That's enough. 20-minute break.

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:00.939 position:50% align:center
I heard you stayed late
practicing on your own

00:08:01.022 --> 00:08:02.941 position:50% align:center
last night, too.

00:08:03.024 --> 00:08:05.485 position:50% align:center
Listen, I appreciate
your enthusiasm,

00:08:05.568 --> 00:08:06.778 position:50% align:center
but before a competition--

00:08:06.861 --> 00:08:08.029 position:50% align:center
Yes, I know.

00:08:08.113 --> 00:08:10.365 position:50% align:center
Don't push myself
and rest my body.

00:08:10.448 --> 00:08:13.493 position:50% align:center
Thing is, I'm this
team's ace. So...

00:08:15.286 --> 00:08:16.871 position:50% align:center
With one lead, their
performance has a greater

00:08:16.955 --> 00:08:18.581 position:50% align:center
impact on the score.

00:08:18.665 --> 00:08:20.834 position:50% align:center
I won't let this end
before making finals!

00:08:26.881 --> 00:08:29.217 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI]
One, two, three, four.

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:31.553 position:50% align:center
One, two, three, four. One.

00:08:33.638 --> 00:08:34.639 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI chuckles]

00:08:36.975 --> 00:08:38.560 position:50% align:center
So, you're still at it, then?

00:08:38.643 --> 00:08:39.769 position:50% align:center
Oh. Manager.

00:08:39.853 --> 00:08:41.146 position:50% align:center
How long have you been here?

00:08:41.229 --> 00:08:43.982 position:50% align:center
Don't worry. I've still
got changes of clothes.

00:08:44.065 --> 00:08:45.233 position:50% align:center
Where are the others?

00:08:45.316 --> 00:08:46.359 position:50% align:center
[MANAGER A]
I sent them home.

00:08:46.443 --> 00:08:48.153 position:50% align:center
They had a shoot
hiking a mountain.

00:08:48.236 --> 00:08:50.280 position:50% align:center
Wanted to play it safe.

00:08:50.363 --> 00:08:51.906 position:50% align:center
Yeah, that sounds rough.

00:08:51.990 --> 00:08:53.658 position:50% align:center
Please finish up
soon, all right?

00:08:53.742 --> 00:08:55.035 position:50% align:center
[KUONJI]
'Kay. Thanks.

00:09:01.416 --> 00:09:03.126 position:50% align:center
[TERAUCHI] Kiriyama, Yuki,
and I are gonna go watch

00:09:03.209 --> 00:09:05.378 position:50% align:center
the eighth competition today.

00:09:05.462 --> 00:09:07.047 position:50% align:center
It's not too far from here.

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:09.966 position:50% align:center
And I'll be tagging along
to scout the enemy.

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:11.259 position:50% align:center
What'll you guys do?

00:09:11.343 --> 00:09:12.761 position:50% align:center
I'm gonna be practicing.

00:09:12.844 --> 00:09:15.597 position:50% align:center
Same here.
Gotta work some iffy spots.

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:17.223 position:50% align:center
I'm staying 'cause
I promised Jonouchi

00:09:17.307 --> 00:09:18.725 position:50% align:center
I'd be his practice partner.

00:09:18.808 --> 00:09:20.894 position:50% align:center
And of course, I'll be
here practicing, too.

00:09:22.604 --> 00:09:23.646 position:50% align:center
Well, this blows.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:24.981 position:50% align:center
Why would you bother
asking if I don't

00:09:25.065 --> 00:09:26.399 position:50% align:center
have a choice, anyway?

00:09:27.984 --> 00:09:29.527 position:50% align:center
[ANNOUNCER B] We're close
to the finish, folks!

00:09:29.611 --> 00:09:31.654 position:50% align:center
With the chance to skate
in the Grand Prix finals

00:09:31.738 --> 00:09:34.074 position:50% align:center
on the line, it's the eighth
and last competition

00:09:34.157 --> 00:09:35.700 position:50% align:center
of the Boys' High
School Skate-Leading

00:09:35.784 --> 00:09:37.285 position:50% align:center
Grand Prix!

00:09:37.369 --> 00:09:39.162 position:50% align:center
For better or worse,
today will decide

00:09:39.245 --> 00:09:40.455 position:50% align:center
which six teams
will be competing

00:09:40.538 --> 00:09:42.749 position:50% align:center
in the Grand Prix finals!

00:09:42.832 --> 00:09:45.669 position:50% align:center
But we have a rare encounter
of two top-class schools.

00:09:45.752 --> 00:09:47.170 position:50% align:center
Yeah, we sure do.

00:09:47.253 --> 00:09:49.255 position:50% align:center
First, we have
Kogahara High School,

00:09:49.339 --> 00:09:51.800 position:50% align:center
which is headed up by
their ace, Himekawa.

00:09:51.883 --> 00:09:53.593 position:50% align:center
Skating against them,
we have Yokohama Super

00:09:53.677 --> 00:09:56.346 position:50% align:center
Global High School,
led by their ace, Kuonji.

00:09:56.429 --> 00:09:57.972 position:50% align:center
It's an exciting pairing!

00:09:58.056 --> 00:10:00.767 position:50% align:center
[ANNOUNCER B] The fateful eighth
competition will soon begin!

